On Tue, 7 Jan 2003, Seairth Jacobs wrote:

&gt; I don&#39;t understand why you would need to maintain a read state of each
&gt; client.  Can you give an example or elaborate a bit?
&gt;
&gt; ---
&gt; Seairth Jacobs
&gt; seairth@...
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; ----- Original Message -----
&gt; From: &quot;S. Alexander Jacobson&quot; &lt;alex@...&gt;
&gt; To: &quot;Seairth Jacobs&quot; &lt;seairth@...&gt;
&gt; Cc: &lt;rest-discuss@yahoogroups.com&gt;
&gt; Sent: Tuesday, January 07, 2003 11:44 AM
&gt; Subject: Re: [rest-discuss] ReST and Representing Mailboxes
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; &gt; If you accepted receive-since, you could always
&gt; &gt; refer to a particular message-id.  I just think
&gt; &gt; either version violates the opacity of URLs.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The problem with using POST or DELETE is that the
&gt; &gt; server now has to maintain read state for each
&gt; &gt; client and you now have an administrative process
&gt; &gt; each time you add a client.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -Alex-
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On Tue, 7 Jan 2003, Seairth Jacobs wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Using something like &quot;receive-since&quot; (I am assuming a timestamp here)
&gt; means
&gt; &gt; &gt; that you have to keep track of the time differences between the client
&gt; and
&gt; &gt; &gt; server, since you need to query the server according to its own time,
&gt; not
&gt; &gt; &gt; the clients.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I think you would do better to have an &quot;inbox&quot; URI, which only contains
&gt; new
&gt; &gt; &gt; messages.  Once you have received a specific message (indicated via the
&gt; &gt; &gt; inbox), POST its URI to the URI of the mail resource you want it to be
&gt; put
&gt; &gt; &gt; in:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; POST /mail/trash
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; http://sample.invalid/mail/inbox/0013
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; This would remove the link from the inbox and place it in the &quot;trash&quot;.
&gt; Of
&gt; &gt; &gt; course, you could always just DELETE the URI directly if you were done
&gt; with
&gt; &gt; &gt; it.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; At any rate, all you would ever have to do to check for mail would be to
&gt; &gt; &gt; &quot;GET /mail/inbox&quot;.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Simple and clean... I think.  :)
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; ---
&gt; &gt; &gt; Seairth Jacobs
&gt; &gt; &gt; seairth@...
